    "The mixing phenomenon of clastic particles with different grain sizes refers to the process by which particles of varying sizes are distributed within a sedimentary environment.",
    "This process is influenced by factors such as fluid dynamics, sediment transport mechanisms, and depositional environments.",
    "The mixing can result in graded bedding.",
    "Graded bedding is where particle sizes are sorted by size due to settling velocities.",
    "The mixing can also result in poorly sorted deposits.",
    "Poorly sorted deposits are where a wide range of grain sizes are intermixed.",
    "The degree of mixing is often quantified using statistical measures like the sorting coefficient.",
    "The sorting coefficient describes the uniformity of grain sizes within a sample.",
    "Sorting is often expressed in phi units.",
    "A lower phi value indicates well-sorted sediments.",
    "A higher phi value indicates poorly sorted sediments."
] 

